Introduction

In this project I am going to be examining a dataset of home characteristics in King County, WA. I will use the variables in the dataset to attempt to predict home prices.

Reading in The Data

Here we will remove zip code, sqft of the basement (collinear with sqft_living), and year renovated (collinear with year built)

homes = read.csv('kc_house_data.csv')

homes_feat = select(homes, -1:-2)

homes_feat$renovated = ifelse(homes_feat$yr_renovated>0,1,0) # Indicates if a house has been remodeled
homes_feat$basement = ifelse(homes_feat$sqft_basement>0,1,0) # Indicated if a house has a basement


homes_feat = select(homes_feat, -12, -14, -15) # remove zipcode, sqft basement, and year renovated

Creating the Training and Test Set

In this example we will work with a 65% train test split, from past work with this dataset the 65% split appears to produce better results than an 80% or 50% split.

set.seed(1)
train = sample(1:nrow(homes_feat), .65*nrow(homes_feat))
test = -train

Formal Analysis

Bagging - General

Model Performance improves dramatically with the use of bagged decision trees. We use ntree = 35 as this has given good results with this dataset in the past. Best RMSE = $129,413.10 (65% training set).

set.seed(1)
bag.homes = randomForest(price~., data=homes_feat, subset=train, mtry=17, ntree=35, importance=T)
  yhat.bag = predict(bag.homes, homes_feat[test,])
  {plot(yhat.bag, homes_feat[test,1], pch = 20)
  abline(0,1)};

  mse = mean((yhat.bag-homes_feat[test,1])^2)

Random Forest - General

Here we have 17 total predictors so we try m= Sqrt(17) = ~4 and m= 18/3 = ~6. It appears that m = 6 performs a bit better. After trying ntree = 25, 30, 35, 40; we conclude 35 leads to best model performance. A cross validation could improve results. Bedrooms, bathrooms, and sqft_living appear to be the most important predictors. Best RMSE = $136,824.50 (65% training set)

Boosting

Here we will use the xgboost package for faster runtime. We will need a model matrix.

#Create Model Matrix
x=model.matrix(price~.,homes_feat)[,-1]
y=homes_feat$price

features_train = x[train,]
response_train = y[train]

features_test = x[test,]
response_test = y[test]

Creating a boosted model.

We start by trying some numbers and seeing what works decent for the parameter values, later we will use a grid search to find the best values.

  • Eta: (learning rate)
  • max_depth: (interaction depth)
  • min_child_weight: (min observations in a terminal node)
  • subsample: allows for stochastic gradient descent (this allows xgboost to randomly sample training data before growing trees)

The RMSE from this first attempt was $128,942.40.

set.seed(1)
params <- list(
  eta = .3,
  max_depth = 5,
  min_child_weight = 5,
  subsample = .8, 
  colsample_bytree = 1
)

xgb.fit1 <- xgboost(
  data = features_train,
  label = response_train,
  params = params,
  nrounds = 964,
  objective = "reg:linear",  # for regression models
  verbose = 0,               # silent,
)

  preds = predict(xgb.fit1,features_test)
  mse = mean((preds-response_test)^2)
  rmse = sqrt(mean((preds-response_test)^2));
  
  mse

Grid Search.

We can use a grid search to help find the optimal tuning parameters, we only try a few here since this can take a long time to finish compiling. Setting subsample to .8 allows for stochastic gradient descent.

hyper_grid <- expand.grid(
  eta = c(.05, .1, .15),
  max_depth = c(1, 3, 5),
  min_child_weight = c(2, 3, 5),
  subsample = .8, 
  colsample_bytree = 1,
  optimal_trees = 0,               # a place to dump results
  min_RMSE = 0                     # a place to dump results
)

for(i in 1:nrow(hyper_grid)) {
  
  # create parameter list
  params <- list(
    eta = hyper_grid$eta[i],
    max_depth = hyper_grid$max_depth[i],
    min_child_weight = hyper_grid$min_child_weight[i],
    subsample = hyper_grid$subsample[i],
    colsample_bytree = hyper_grid$colsample_bytree[i]
  )
  
  # reproducibility
  set.seed(1)
  
  # train model
  xgb.tune <- xgb.cv(
    params = params,
    data = features_train,
    label = response_train,
    nrounds = 5000,
    nfold = 5,
    objective = "reg:linear",  # for regression models
    verbose = 0,               # silent,
    early_stopping_rounds = 10 # stop if no improvement for 10 consecutive trees
  )
  
  # add min training error and trees to grid
  hyper_grid$optimal_trees[i] <- which.min(xgb.tune$evaluation_log$test_rmse_mean)
  hyper_grid$min_RMSE[i] <- min(xgb.tune$evaluation_log$test_rmse_mean)
}

hyper_grid %>%
  dplyr::arrange(min_RMSE) %>%
  head(10)

Fitting the final model

After obtaining the optimal hyperparameters from the grid search we can fit the best model on the training data. Eta = .05 (learning rate) max_depth = 3 (interaction depth) min_child_weight = 3 (min observations in a terminal node) subsample = .8 (allows xgboost to randomly sample training data before growing trees) Final model RMSE is $123,042.40, a huge reduction compared to the linear model and single decision tree.

set.seed(1)
params <- list(
  eta = .05,
  max_depth = 3,
  min_child_weight = 3,
  subsample = .80,
  colsample_bytree = 1
)

xgb.fit.final <- xgboost(
  data = features_train,
  label = response_train,
  params = params,
  nrounds = 1207,
  objective = "reg:linear",  # for regression models
  verbose = 0,               # silent,
)

  preds = predict(xgb.fit.final,features_test)
  mse = mean((preds-response_test)^2)
  rmse = sqrt(mean((preds-response_test)^2));

  mse

Single Layer Neural Network With Cross Validation.

Now we will see if we can get even better results by using a single layer neural network. Since we have a variety of unit scales in our predictors we standardize the dataset before beginning. We use 10 fold cross validation to pick the optimal number of hidden nodes which was found to be 25. Best RMSE = $152,403.60

maxs <- apply(homes_feat[,], 2, max)
mins <- apply(homes_feat[,], 2, min)

scaled.data <- as.data.frame(scale(homes_feat[,],center = mins, scale = maxs - mins))


scale.train = scaled.data[train, ]
scale.test = scaled.data[test, ]

set.seed(1)
fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv",
                           number = 10) # 10-fold CV
nnetGrid <-  expand.grid(size = c(3,5,10,15,20,25), decay = 0)
homes.nn <- train(price~., data=scale.train, method='nnet', 
                    trace = F,
                    trControl = fitControl,
                    tuneGrid = nnetGrid,
                    linout = TRUE)
